column3: To tighten the bolts on a chair using the allen key, the robotic hand must wrap around the longer arm of the allen key to provide sufficient torque and leverage. The bent tip of the allen key is used to fit into the bolt, so it must remain free for insertion.The best region to grip is the longer, straight arm of the allen key, starting just after the bent portion and extending towards the end of the tool. This will provide a good grip and allow for easy application of force.Given the image, the normalized bounding box is approximately:- x1: 0.25 (about a quarter from left)- y1: 0.58 (slightly below horizontal center)- x2: 0.91 (near the right edge)- y2: 0.75 (below horizontal center)This box covers the straight main shaft and leaves the bent tip free for use.```json{hand: [0.25, 0.58, 0.91, 0.75]}```

To vaccinate a patient using this syringe, the robotic index finger should stabilize the syringe on its barrel near the needle to provide control and support. The thumb should be placed on the plunger's top to push it down and inject the vaccine.Analyzing the image:- The syringe barrel is the translucent cylinder.- The plunger has a white top at the right side.- The needle tip is on the left side.The index finger should grip the barrel about one third from the needle tip (left side).The thumb should press down on the white plunger top at the right end.Normalized bounding boxes:- The syringe occupies roughly from x=0.15 to x=0.85.- The needle tip is around x=0.15 - 0.25.- The barrel extends from about x=0.25 to 0.75.- The plunger top lies at about x=0.85 - 0.95.Index finger bounding box:- Horizontally: around 0.28 to 0.43 (around barrel near needle).- Vertically: approximately 0.35 to 0.65 (middle vertical section of barrel).Thumb bounding box:- Horizontally: around 0.83 to 0.95 (plunger top).- Vertically: approximately 0.55 to 0.75 (plunger top height).{ index: [0.28, 0.35, 0.43, 0.65], thumb: [0.83, 0.55, 0.95, 0.75]}

The allen key in the image has a T-shaped handle on the right side and a long metal shaft on the left side, which is used to tighten bolts. To maximize torque and effective use, the robotic hand should grip the handle where it has a thick, ergonomic design to provide a firm hold.The best region for the hand to wrap around is the black and yellow handle area near the middle-right part of the image because:- This part has a thick and contoured grip meant for holding.- It allows the user to apply rotational force using the longer shaft part.- The hand must have one continuous contact region, so selecting the handle portion is ideal.Estimating normalized coordinates based on the image size:- Top-left corner of the handle grip: around (0.46, 0.28)- Bottom-right corner of the handle grip: around (0.70, 0.55)Output:```json{hand : [0.46, 0.28, 0.70, 0.55]}```

The hammer comprises a metal head and a handle with a black grip at the top. The best region for the robotic hand to safely and effectively hold the hammer is the black grip area, as it is designed for ergonomic grasp and ensures a firm hold.Analyzing the image:- The handle with the black grip starts approximately at 0.3 of the height from the top and ends near the midpoint.- The grip spans the full width of the handle, roughly between 0.4 and 0.6 normalized width.Hence, the bounding box for the hand grip region would be:{hand: [0.4, 0.3, 0.6, 0.5]}

To identify the best region for the robotic hand to wrap around the vertical bar handle, I observe the following:- The vertical bar handle is located on the right side of the door.- The handle is long and narrow, covering a vertical span roughly from the middle of the door height to a bit above the bottom.- The optimal grasp region would be the middle part of the vertical bar handle, as that is where a firm grip can be established.- The hand should wrap around the handle's vertical length for secure holding.Based on the image dimensions and perspective, the vertical handle in normalized coordinates would be roughly between:- Horizontally: starting about 0.85 (near the right edge of the door) to 0.92 (edge of handle width).- Vertically: roughly from 0.55 to 0.75 (middle to lower-middle).Therefore, the bounding box for the robotic hand to wrap around the door handle is approximately:[x1, y1, x2, y2] = [0.85, 0.55, 0.92, 0.75]```json{hand : [0.85, 0.55, 0.92, 0.75]}```

The dart's tip is already embedded in the bullseye, indicating that's where the dart will land. To throw a bullseye efficiently, the fingers should grip the dart near its center of gravity, just behind the metal barrel. - The thumb should press on one side of the barrel, providing control and stability.- The index finger should rest on the opposite side, extending slightly along the barrel to guide the throw.Analyzing the dart in the image:- The metal barrel is the metallic part just to the right of the dart in the image.- The contact area should be roughly centered mid-barrel.Estimated normalized coordinates for finger placements based on the dart's position in the image:- Thumb: Around the lower left side of the barrel (since the dart is pointing right)- Index: Around the upper right side of the barrelBounding box thumb (normalized): roughly [0.48, 0.46, 0.53, 0.58]Bounding box index (normalized): roughly [0.55, 0.38, 0.60, 0.50]```json{ index: [0.55, 0.38, 0.60, 0.50], thumb: [0.48, 0.46, 0.53, 0.58]}```

To bowl a strike, the robotic index finger and thumb must be placed in the two different holes on the bowling ball that are meant for finger insertion. The third hole is typically for the middle finger and does not hold the thumb or index finger. The blue hole on the right side of the image is best suited for the index finger because it appears to be one of the finger-sized holes with enough clearance. The red hole on the left side of the ball is suitable for the thumb as it is larger and located on the opposite side, offering a good grip and control.Now I will approximate the bounding boxes for these two holes:- Index finger (blue hole): roughly around the blue holes located in the lower right quadrant area of the ball.- Thumb (red hole): roughly around the red hole located in the left quadrant area of the ball.Normalized coordinates:- Image width approximately 1 unit.- Image height approximately 1 unit.For the blue hole (index finger), the top-left corner can be estimated around x=0.75, y=0.62 and bottom-right around x=0.88, y=0.78.For the red hole (thumb), the top-left corner can be estimated around x=0.13, y=0.42 and bottom-right around x=0.28, y=0.58.```json{ index: [0.75, 0.62, 0.88, 0.78], thumb: [0.13, 0.42, 0.28, 0.58]}```

This is the black rubberized section located roughly in the middle of the handle.Looking at the image, this gripping area is between the battery section at the rear and the yellow body of the drill near the front. The best placement for the robotic fingertip is on the front-facing portion of this black handle part, enabling an immediate and secure use of the trigger and balance of the drill.The approximate normalized bounding box coordinates for this area are:- x1 (top-left x): about 0.38 (a bit right of the left edge)- y1 (top-left y): about 0.48 (mid height from the top)- x2 (bottom-right x): about 0.52 (close to center width)- y2 (bottom-right y): about 0.63 (slightly below mid height)This bounding box covers the gripping rubber on the handle surface facing forward.```json{index: [0.38, 0.48, 0.52, 0.63]}```
